O:a) "\\(-2x^3\\)", b) "\\(2x^{-3}\\)", c) "\\(-2x^{-3}\\)", d) "\\(2x^3\\)"
R:"\\(f(x) = x^{-2} \\Rightarrow f'(x) = -2x^{-3}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Derivative of \\(x^3\\) with respect to \\(x^3\\) is:"
A:"B"
O:a) "0", b) "1", c) "\\(3x^2\\)", d) "\\(x^3\\)"
R:"Let \\(u = x^3\\). \\(\\frac{du}{du} = 1\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\frac{d}{dx}(2^x)\\) equals:"
A:"C"
O:a) "\\(2x\\)", b) "\\(2x \\ln x\\)", c) "\\(2^x \\ln 2\\)", d) "\\(2x \\ln 2\\)"
R:"The derivative of an exponential function \\(a^x\\) is \\(a^x \\ln a\\)."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(f(x) = \\cos x\\) then \\(\\frac{d}{dx} f(\\tan x)\\) equals:"
A:"A"
O:a) "\\(-\\sin(\\tan x) \\sec^2 x\\)", b) "\\(-\\csc^2 x\\)", c) "\\(\\sec^2 x\\)", d) "\\(-\\cos^2 x\\)"R:"By Chain Rule: \\(f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x) = -\\sin(\\tan x) \\cdot \\sec^2 x\\)."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(f(x) = \\cos x\\) then \\(f(0)\\) equals:"
A:"B"
O:a) "0", b) "1", c) "-1", d) "None of these"
R:"\\(\\cos(0) = 1\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\int \\frac{dx}{ax+b}\\) equals:"
A:"B"
O:a) "\\(a \\ln(ax+b) + c\\)", b) "\\(\\frac{1}{a} \\ln(ax+b) + c\\)", c) "\\(-a \\ln(ax+b) + c\\)", d) "\\(\\frac{-1}{a} \\ln(ax+b) + c\\)"
R:"Integration yields \\(\\frac{1}{a} \\ln|ax+b| + C\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\int a^x dx\\) equals:"
A:"C"
O:a) "\\(a^x \\cos + c\\)", b) "\\(\\frac{-\\cos a^x}{\\ln a} + c\\)", c) "\\(\\frac{a^x}{\\ln a} + c\\)", d) "\\(a^x \\cos \\cdot \\ln a + c\\)"
R:"Standard integral of exponential function."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\int \\frac{dx}{x^2+9}\\) equals:"
A:"B"
O:a) "\\(\\frac{1}{3} \\sec^{-1}(\\frac{x}{3}) + c\\)", b) "\\(\\frac{1}{3} \\tan^{-1}(\\frac{x}{3}) + c\\)", c) "\\(\\frac{1}{3} \\cos^{-1}(\\frac{x}{3}) + c\\)", d) "\\(\\frac{1}{9} \\tan^{-1}(\\frac{x}{9}) + c\\)"
R:"Using \\(\\int \\frac{dx}{x^2+a^2} = \\frac{1}{a} \\tan^{-1}(\\frac{x}{a})\\) where \\(a=3\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\int_0^{1/\\sqrt{2}} \\frac{dx}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}\\) equals:"
A:"C"
O:a) "\\(\\pi/6\\)", b) "\\(\\pi/3\\)", c) "\\(\\pi/4\\)", d) "\\(-\\pi/6\\)"
R:"Integral is \\([\\sin^{-1} x]_0^{1/\\sqrt{2}} = \\sin^{-1}(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}) - 0 = \\frac{\\pi}{4}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The distance between points (2,2) and (3,3) is:"
A:"B"
O:a) "\\(\\sqrt{10}\\)", b) "\\(\\sqrt{2}\\)", c) "\\(\\sqrt{5}\\)", d) "2"
R:"Distance \\(d = \\sqrt{(3-2)^2 + (3-2)^2} = \\sqrt{1+1} = \\sqrt{2}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Lines with slopes \\(m_1, m_2\\) are perpendicular if:"
A:"A"
O:a) "\\(m_1 m_2 = -1\\)", b) "\\(m_1 m_2 = 1\\)", c) "\\(m_1 = m_2\\)", d) "\\(m_1 + m_2 = 0\\)"
R:"Condition for perpendicular lines is product of slopes = -1."}

q {
Q:"The equation of the line bisecting the first and third quadrants is:"
A:"A"
O:a) "\\(y = x\\)", b) "\\(y = -x\\)", c) "\\(y = a\\)", d) "\\(x = a\\)"
R:"This line makes a 45 degree angle with axes, so slope is 1 and passes through origin."
}

q {
Q:"The perpendicular distance of the line \\(12x + 5y = 7\\) from the origin is:"
A:"A"
O:a) "\\(\\frac{7}{13}\\)", b) "\\(\\frac{13}{7}\\)", c) "\\(\\frac{17}{13}\\)", d) "\\(\\frac{1}{13}\\)"
R:"Distance formula \\(d = \\frac{|Ax_0 + By_0 + C|}{\\sqrt{A^2+B^2}} = \\frac{|-7|}{\\sqrt{144+25}} = \\frac{7}{13}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Point (1,2) satisfies the inequality:"
A:"B"
O:a) "\\(2x+y > 8\\)", b) "\\(2x+y \\leq 6\\)", c) "\\(2x-y > 1\\)", d) "\\(2x+3y < 2\\)"
R:"Check (1,2) in B: \\(2(1)+2 = 4 \\leq 6\\) (True). Others: A) 4>8 (F), C) 0>1 (F), D) 8<2 (F)."
}

q {
Q:"The equation of the normal to the circle \\(x^2+y^2=25\\) at (4,3) is:"
A:"A"
O:a) "\\(3x - 4y = 0\\)", b) "\\(3x - 4y = 5\\)", c) "\\(4x + 3y = 5\\)", d) "\\(4x + 3y = 25\\)"
R:"The normal passes through the center (0,0) and point (4,3). Slope \\(m = 3/4\\). Eq: \\(y = \\frac{3}{4}x \\Rightarrow 4y = 3x \\Rightarrow 3x - 4y = 0\\)."
}

meta Subj1:"Physics"/Chap1:"Measurements & Vectors"/Topi1:"Scalars, Vectors & Motion"/Type1:K/Diff1:E/Stem1:"conceptual"/

q {
Q:"Which of the following is a scalar quantity?"
A:"A"
O:a) "Density", b) "Displacement", c) "Torque", d) "Weight"
R:"Density has magnitude only. The others are vectors."
}

q {
Q:"Which of the following is the only vector quantity?"
A:"D"
O:a) "Temperature", b) "Energy", c) "Power", d) "Momentum"
R:"Momentum is mass times velocity (vector). Others are scalars."
}

q {
Q:"Which list consists only of vectors?"
A:"D"
O:a) "Time, temperature, velocity", b) "Force, volume, momentum", c) "Velocity, acceleration, mass", d) "Force, acceleration, velocity"R:"Force, acceleration, and velocity are all vector quantities."
}

q {
Q:"The rectangular components of a vector have an angle between them of:"
A:"C"
O:a) "\\(0^\\circ\\)", b) "\\(60^\\circ\\)", c) "\\(90^\\circ\\)", d) "\\(120^\\circ\\)"
R:"Rectangular components are orthogonal (perpendicular)."
}

q {
Q:"A force of 10N acts along the y-axis. Its component along the z-axis is:"
A:"D"
O:a) "10N", b) "20N", c) "100N", d) "Zero"
R:"Since the force is perpendicular to the z-axis, the projection (component) on z is zero."
}

q {
Q:"Resultant of two forces is minimum when the angle between them is:"
A:"D"
O:a) "\\(0^\\circ\\)", b) "\\(60^\\circ\\)", c) "\\(120^\\circ\\)", d) "\\(180^\\circ\\)"
R:"When forces are opposite (\\(180^\\circ\\)), they subtract, giving the minimum magnitude."
}

q {
Q:"Two forces 10N and 15N act in the same direction. Resultant is:"
A:"C"
O:a) "Zero", b) "5N", c) "25N", d) "150N"
R:"Same direction implies addition: \\(10 + 15 = 25\\) N."
}

q {
Q:"If dot product of two non-zero vectors vanishes, they are:"
A:"C"
O:a) "In same direction", b) "Opposite", c) "Perpendicular", d) "Zero"
R:"Dot product zero implies \\(\\cos \\theta = 0 \\Rightarrow \\theta = 90^\\circ\\)."
}

q {
Q:"If vectors A and B are parallel, then A.B is equal to:"
A:"B"
O:a) "Zero", b) "AB", c) "A+B", d) "A-B"
R:"\\(\\vec{A} \\cdot \\vec{B} = AB \\cos 0 = AB\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Vector product of two vectors is zero when they are:"
A:"A"
O:a) "Parallel", b) "Perpendicular", c) "Equal", d) "Inclined at 60"
R:"Cross product magnitude is \\(AB \\sin \\theta\\). Zero when \\(\\sin \\theta = 0\\) (parallel)."}

q {
Q:"If \\(\\vec{A} \\times \\vec{B}\\) points along positive z-axis, vectors A and B must lie in:"
A:"C"
O:a) "xz-plane", b) "yz-plane", c) "xy-plane", d) "None"
R:"Cross product is perpendicular to the plane containing A and B. If result is z, plane is xy."
}

q {
Q:"Position vector of a point in xz-plane is given by:"
A:"D"
O:a) "\\(\\vec{r} = x\\hat{i} + y\\hat{j}\\)", b) "\\(\\vec{r} = y\\hat{i} + z\\hat{k}\\)", c) "\\(\\vec{r} = x\\hat{i} + y\\hat{j} + z\\hat{k}\\)", d) "\\(\\vec{r} = x\\hat{i} + z\\hat{k}\\)"
R:"In xz-plane, the y-component is zero."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(\\vec{A}\\) and \\(\\vec{B}\\) are in xy-plane, direction of \\(\\vec{A} \\times \\vec{B}\\) is:"
A:"D"
O:a) "Along B", b) "Along x-axis", c) "Along y-axis", d) "Along z-axis"
R:"Cross product of vectors in xy-plane is along z-axis."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(\\vec{A} \\cdot \\vec{B} = 0\\) and \\(\\vec{A} \\times \\vec{B} = 0\\), then:"
A:"D"
O:a) "A and B are perpendicular", b) "A and B are parallel", c) "A and B are anti-parallel", d) "Either A or B is a null vector"
R:"Dot product 0 means perpendicular. Cross product 0 means parallel. Both true only if one vector is zero."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\hat{k} \\times \\hat{j}\\) equals:"
A:"D"
O:a) "\\(\\hat{i}\\)", b) "\\(\\hat{j}\\)", c) "\\(-\\hat{k}\\)", d) "\\(-\\hat{i}\\)"
R:"By right hand rule, \\(\\hat{k} \\times \\hat{j} = -\\hat{i}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"A bomb is dropped from a plane moving at 600 km/h. Time to ground is 5s. Altitude is approx:"
A:"C"
O:a) "50 m", b) "75 m", c) "125 m", d) "250 m"
R:"Vertical motion is independent of horizontal. \\(h = \\frac{1}{2} g t^2 \\approx 0.5 \\times 10 \\times 25 = 125\\) m."
}

q {
Q:"If instantaneous and average velocities are equal, the body moves with:"
A:"D"
O:a) "Uniform acceleration", b) "Uniform speed", c) "Variable velocity", d) "Uniform velocity"
R:"Constant velocity implies instantaneous velocity is always equal to average velocity."
}
q {
Q:"Time to cover 490m in free fall is:"
A:"A"
O:a) "10 sec", b) "100 sec", c) "9.8 sec", d) "4.9 sec"
R:"\\(t = \\sqrt{2h/g} = \\sqrt{2(490)/9.8} = \\sqrt{100} = 10\\) s."
}

q {
Q:"Reaction force of ground when jumping is:"
A:"A"
O:a) "Greater than weight", b) "Smaller than weight", c) "Equal to weight", d) "Zero"
R:"To accelerate upwards, net force must be upwards, so Normal > Weight."
}

q {
Q:"Gun recoil velocity compared to bullet velocity is:"
A:"A"
O:a) "Less than bullet", b) "Equal", c) "Greater", d) "None"
R:"By momentum conservation, since gun mass is much larger, its velocity is much smaller."
}

q {
Q:"Law applicable to rocket motion in space:"
A:"D"
O:a) "Conservation of mass", b) "Conservation of energy", c) "Conservation of angular momentum", d) "Conservation of linear momentum"
R:"Rockets work by expelling mass to conserve momentum."
}

q {
Q:"Fog droplet after terminal velocity falls with acceleration:"
A:"D"
O:a) "Equal to g", b) "Less than g", c) "Greater than g", d) "Equal to zero"
R:"At terminal velocity, net force is zero, so acceleration is zero."
}

q {
Q:"Max acceleration of ball on smooth incline occurs at angle:"
A:"A"
O:a) "\\(90^\\circ\\)", b) "\\(60^\\circ\\)", c) "\\(30^\\circ\\)", d) "\\(0^\\circ\\)"
R:"\\(a = g \\sin \\theta\\), maximum at \\(\\sin 90^\\circ = 1\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Force 4N on 2kg for 2s. Rate of change of momentum is:"
A:"C"
O:a) "1 kg m/s²", b) "2 kg m/s²", c) "4 kg m/s²", d) "8 kg m/s²"
R:"Rate of change of momentum equals Force (Newton's 2nd Law)."
}
q {
Q:"Elevator going up with constant acceleration. Push on floor is:"
A:"B"
O:a) "Equal to weight", b) "Greater than weight", c) "Less than weight", d) "Zero"
R:"\\(N = m(g+a)\\). Since \\(a > 0\\), \\(N > mg\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Particle in horizontal circle with constant angular velocity:"
A:"B"
O:a) "Momentum constant, KE varies", b) "KE constant, Momentum varies", c) "Both constant", d) "Neither constant"
R:"Speed constant implies KE constant. Direction changes implies momentum (vector) varies."
}

q {
Q:"Point on rim moves 0.2m for 0.1 rad turn. Radius is:"
A:"B"
O:a) "0.5m", b) "2 m", c) "0.2 m", d) "20 m"
R:"\\(s = r\\theta \\Rightarrow r = s/\\theta = 0.2 / 0.1 = 2\\) m."
}

q {
Q:"Boltzmann constant value is:"
A:"B"
O:a) "1.38 J/K", b) "\\(1.38 \\times 10^{-23}\\) J/K", c) "\\(6.21 \\times 10^{-12}\\)", d) "None"
R:"Standard constant value."
}

q {
Q:"Least distance of distinct vision in man is:"
A:"D"
O:a) "10 cm", b) "20 cm", c) "15 cm", d) "25 cm"
R:"Standard near point distance."
}

q {
Q:"Impulse when 1000N acts for 0.01s:"
A:"C"
O:a) "100 N-s", b) "50 N-s", c) "10 N-s", d) "5 N-s"
R:"Impulse \\(J = F \\Delta t = 1000 \\times 0.01 = 10\\) N-s."
}

q {
Q:"Projectile moving upwards, vertical component of velocity:"
A:"B"
O:a) "Remains constant", b) "Decreases", c) "Increases", d) "Equals horizontal"
R:"Gravity opposes upward motion, decreasing vertical velocity."
}

q {Q:"At highest point, projectile vertical velocity is:"
A:"B"
O:a) "Maximum", b) "Minimum", c) "Equal to horizontal", d) "Equal to initial"
R:"Vertical velocity becomes zero (minimum magnitude) at the peak."
}

q {
Q:"Speed of efflux equal to velocity gained falling through height. This is:"
A:"D"
O:a) "Bernoulli’s theorem", b) "Law of continuity", c) "Fluid law", d) "Torricelli’s theorem"
R:"Definition of Torricelli's theorem."
}

q {
Q:"Angular momentum is defined as:"
A:"B"
O:a) "Dot product of r and p", b) "Cross product of r and p", c) "Simple product", d) "Product of distance and momentum"
R:"\\(\\vec{L} = \\vec{r} \\times \\vec{p}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Newton's Law of Gravitation states force is proportional to:"
A:"C"
O:a) "Product of mass and distance", b) "Square of distance", c) "Product of their masses", d) "Square of masses"
R:"Force is proportional to product of masses and inversely proportional to square of distance."
}

q {
Q:"Distance doubled, masses doubled. Gravitational force will:"
A:"C"
O:a) "Increase 4x", b) "Decrease 4x", c) "Remain constant", d) "Remain constant"
R:"\\(F' = G \\frac{(2m)(2m)}{(2r)^2} = G \\frac{4m^2}{4r^2} = F\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Work done by force is maximum when:"
A:"B"
O:a) "Displacement is zero", b) "Force is parallel to displacement", c) "Force is perpendicular", d) "Force is anti-parallel"
R:"\\(W = Fd \\cos 0\\) is maximum."
}

q {
Q:"Power is:"
A:"A"
O:a) "\\(\\vec{F} \\cdot \\vec{V}\\)", b) "\\(\\vec{F} \\times \\vec{V}\\)", c) "\\(F + V\\)", d) "\\(F - V\\)"
R:"Power is the dot product of force and velocity."
}

q {
Q:"In transverse waves, particles vibrate:"A:"C"
O:a) "At rest", b) "Along propagation", c) "Perpendicular to propagation", d) "At 180 deg"
R:"Definition of transverse waves."
}

q {
Q:"In longitudinal waves, particles vibrate:"
A:"A"
O:a) "Parallel to propagation", b) "Perpendicular", c) "Do not move", d) "At 270 deg"
R:"Definition of longitudinal waves."
}

q {
Q:"Speed 100m/s, freq 100Hz. Wavelength is:"
A:"A"
O:a) "1 m", b) "10 m", c) "100 m", d) "1000 m"
R:"\\(\\lambda = v/f = 100/100 = 1\\) m."
}

q {
Q:"When fluid speed is high, pressure is:"
A:"C"
O:a) "No effect", b) "High", c) "Low", d) "Equal to atmospheric"
R:"Bernoulli's principle: higher speed implies lower pressure."
}

q {
Q:"Light wave behavior is proved by:"
A:"D"
O:a) "Interference only", b) "Diffraction & Refraction", c) "Interference & Diffraction", d) "Interference, Diffraction, Refraction"
R:"All listed phenomena demonstrate wave properties."
}

q {
Q:"At high velocity, fluid motion becomes:"
A:"D"
O:a) "Streamline", b) "Circular", c) "Oscillatory", d) "Turbulent"
R:"High velocity leads to turbulence (high Reynolds number)."
}

q {
Q:"Polaroid can be used for:"
A:"D"
O:a) "Headlight glare", b) "Optically active substance conc", c) "Light adjustment", d) "All of them"
R:"Applications of polarization."
}

q {
Q:"Lens thicker in middle, thinner at edge is:"
A:"B"O:a) "Concave", b) "Convex", c) "Plano-concave", d) "Convex-concave"
R:"Definition of convex lens."
}

q {
Q:"Line passing through centers of curvature of lens surfaces is:"
A:"C"
O:a) "Diameter", b) "Radius", c) "Principal axis", d) "Principal focus"
R:"Definition of principal axis."
}

q {
Q:"Double convex lens acts as diverging lens when object is:"
A:"D"
O:a) "At focus", b) "At 2f", c) "Between f and 2f", d) "Within focal length"
R:"When object is within focal length, a convex lens produces a virtual image where rays diverge from a virtual focus, acting somewhat like a diverging lens (magnifying glass effect)."
}

q {
Q:"Temperature determines:"
A:"C"
O:a) "Total energy", b) "Fraction of heat", c) "Ability to transfer heat", d) "Heat content"
R:"Temperature determines the direction of heat flow (ability to transfer)."
}

q {
Q:"Beats difficult to recognize if frequency difference >"
A:"D"
O:a) "2", b) "5", c) "7", d) "10"
R:"Human ear persistence of sound is about 0.1s, limiting beat discrimination to >10Hz."
}

q {
Q:"Source moving towards stationary listener. Frequency:"
A:"C"
O:a) "Same", b) "Decreases", c) "Increases", d) "None"
R:"Doppler effect: approaching source increases perceived frequency."
}

q {
Q:"Triple point of water is:"
A:"B"
O:a) "0 C", b) "273.16 K", c) "100 C", d) "-273 C"
R:"Triple point is exactly 273.16 K (0.01 C)."
}

q {
Q:"Air at 300K, 1atm compressed to 1/20 vol and 30atm. New temp:"
A:"C"
O:a) "9000 K", b) "100 K", c) "450 K", d) "450 C"R:"Ideal gas law \\(PV/T = const\\). \\(T_2 = T_1 (P_2/P_1)(V_2/V_1) = 300 (30/1)(1/20) = 300(1.5) = 450\\) K."
}

q {
Q:"Unit charge experiences 10N. Electric field intensity is:"
A:"C"
O:a) "8 N/C", b) "9 N/C", c) "10 N/C", d) "11 N/C"
R:"\\(E = F/q = 10/1 = 10\\) N/C."
}

passage {
text: "Hiuen Tsang, the famous Chinese traveler, visited Pakistan (then India) in the seventh century. He traveled extensively and stayed for some time in Kanouj, at the court of the great emperor Harshavardhana. He has left for us graphic descriptions of the pomp and ceremony of the royal regalia and the lavish celebrations of Hindu festivals. During one particular festivity at the confluence of the Ganga and Yamuna, many princes would come to participate in the giving of gifts to the poor and needy. How those ancient banks of sacred rivers have heard voices of collective prayers and the shouts of joy of periodic pilgrims! If only the mute stones and steps could tell all the thrills they have witnessed, volumes of stirring stories would flow from them. Hiuen Tsang spent a long period at the famed Nalanda, the great center of learning, where students by the hundreds flocked from all over. It has flourished in the remote century of the Buddha and Mahavira, and now when the Chinese pilgrim visited the place it seemed to have been still full of life and intellectual vigour. For this is what the pilgrim notes: 'The day is not sufficient for asking and answering profound questions. From morning till night they engage in discussions; the old and the young mutually help one another. If such is not an ideal place of learning, then what is?'"

q {
Q:"Why are the writings of Hiuen Tsang considered very important?"
A:"B"
O:a) "He was the first foreign visitor", b) "We get details about the life style of classical Pakistan", c) "He wrote in local language", d) "He was impressed by the way of life"
R:"His writings provide detailed accounts of the culture, festivals, and academic life of the time."
}

q {
Q:"Why did Hiuen Tsang spend considerable time at Nalanda?"
A:"A"
O:a) "It was a renowned center of teaching and learning", b) "He was desirous of learning Buddhist practices", c) "It was a center of pilgrimage", d) "At request of local king"
R:"The passage highlights Nalanda as a 'great center of learning' with 'intellectual vigour'."
}

q {
Q:"The passage refers to all the following EXCEPT:"
A:"A"
O:a) "Footsteps of pilgrims", b) "Voices of collective prayers", c) "Giving of gifts to poor", d) "Lavish celebrations"
R:"While prayers, gifts, and celebrations are explicitly mentioned as being 'heard' or 'seen', footsteps are mentioned in a hypothetical context ('If only mute stones... could tell') rather than a direct observation."
}

q {
Q:"What has been considered as the most significant aspect of Nalanda?"
A:"A"
O:a) "It was a renowned center of teaching and learning", b) "It admitted only foreign students", c) "Princes came there for studies", d) "It witnessed stories of Buddha"
R:"The text focuses on its role as a hub for students and intellectual discussions."
}

q {
Q:"Which of the following is not mentioned in the passage?"
A:"D"
O:a) "Ganga", b) "Mahavira", c) "Nalanda", d) "Takshashila"
R:"Ganga, Mahavira, and Nalanda are mentioned. Takshashila is not."
}
}

meta Subj1:"English"/Chap1:"Grammar & Usage"/Topi1:"Sentence Completion"/Type1:K/Diff1:M/Stem1:"grammar"/
q {
Q:"Miss Watson termed Hock's behavior _____ because in her opinion nothing could excuse his deliberate disregard of her commands."
A:"D"
O:a) "devious", b) "intolerant", c) "Irrevocable", d) "indefensible"
R:"'Indefensible' means incapable of being justified, matching 'nothing could excuse'."
}

q {
Q:"Either the surfing at Maui is _____, or I went there on an off day."
A:"D"
O:a) "Consistent", b) "Thrilling", c) "Invigorating", d) "Overrated"
R:"'Overrated' suggests the experience did not meet the reputation, explaining the disappointment."
}

q {
Q:"Your _____ remarks spoil the effect of your speech; try not to stray from your subject."
A:"B"
O:a) "innocuous", b) "Digressive", c) "Derogatory", d) "Persistent"
R:"'Digressive' means wandering from the main topic."
}

q {
Q:"We need both ornament and implement in our society; we need the artist and the _____."
A:"D"
O:a) "beautician", b) "Writer", c) "politician", d) "Artisan"
R:"An 'Artisan' is a skilled craft worker (implement creator), complementing the artist."
}

q {
Q:"When such _____ remarks are circulated, we can only blame and despise those who produce them."
A:"C"
O:a) "adulatory", b) "Chance", c) "reprehensible", d) "redundant"
R:"'Reprehensible' means deserving blame or censure."
}

q {
Q:"The stereotypical image of masculinity assumes that weeping is _____ 'unmanly' behaviour, and not simply a human reaction which may be _____ by either sex."
A:"D"
O:a) "Inexplicably... repented", b) "Excessively... discerned", c) "Essentially... defined", d) "Inherently... adopted"
R:"'Inherently' suggests an intrinsic quality; 'adopted' means taken on or exhibited."
}

meta Subj1:"English"/Chap1:"Vocabulary & Analogies"/Topi1:"Word Relations & Meanings"/Type1:K/Diff1:E/Stem1:"vocabulary"/

q {
Q:"FRAGILE : BREAK ::"
A:"D"
O:a) "vital: destroy", b) "hostile: invite", c) "vivid: grow", d) "flexible: bend"
R:"Something fragile is prone to break. Something flexible is prone to bend. Property-to-action relationship."}

q {
Q:"TELLER : BANK ::"
A:"C"
O:a) "Artist: museum", b) "Cashier: check", c) "Waiter: restaurant", d) "Borrower: loan"
R:"A teller works in a bank. A waiter works in a restaurant. Professional-to-workplace relationship."
}

q {
Q:"INNING : BASEBALL ::"
A:"A"
O:a) "round: boxing", b) "puck: hockey", c) "touchdown: football", d) "serve: tennis"
R:"An inning is a division of a baseball game. A round is a division of a boxing match."
}

q {
Q:"DEGREE : TEMPERATURE ::"
A:"A"
O:a) "ounce: weight", b) "fathom: volume", c) "mass: energy", d) "time: length"
R:"A degree is a unit of temperature. An ounce is a unit of weight."
}

q {
Q:"PICK : GUITAR ::"
A:"D"
O:a) "peg: ukelele", b) "string: banjo", c) "pipe: organ", d) "bow: violin"
R:"A pick is used to play a guitar. A bow is used to play a violin. Tool-to-instrument relationship."
}

q {
Q:"OMNIPOTENT:"
A:"A"
O:a) "Weak", b) "Strong", c) "Sour", d) "Safe"
R:"Omnipotent means all-powerful. Weak is the antonym."
}

q {
Q:"NERVOUS:"
A:"C"
O:a) "Courageous", b) "Puzzle", c) "Bold", d) "Trainee"
R:"Nervous implies anxiety/lack of confidence. Bold implies fearlessness."
}

q {
Q:"NOTORIOUS:"
A:"A"
O:a) "Renowned", b) "Invincible", c) "Inactive", d) "Fashionable"
R:"Notorious means famous for bad reasons. Renowned means famous for good reasons."
}
q {
Q:"NOCTURNAL:"
A:"B"
O:a) "Patrolling", b) "Daily", c) "Harsh", d) "Marauding"
R:"Nocturnal means active at night. Daily implies daytime activity."
}

q {
Q:"OBDURATE:"
A:"C"
O:a) "Fleeting", b) "Finite", c) "Yielding", d) "Permanent"
R:"Obdurate means stubborn. Yielding means compliant."
}

meta Subj1:"Intelligence"/Chap1:"Logical Reasoning"/Topi1:"Series & Patterns"/Type1:A/Diff1:M/Stem1:"calculation"/

q {
Q:"Look at this series: 28, 25, 5, 21, 18, 5, 14... What comes next?"
A:"A"
O:a) "11, 5", b) "10, 7", c) "11, 8", d) "5, 10"
